The runtime layer.

Recall from notebook one that the daemon does not actually run containers itself. The container runtime supervisor talks to the low-level runtime, which does the namespace, control-group, and process-execution work. You usually never touch this layer, but it is worth knowing the cases where you might.

There are a few alternative low-level runtimes. One is a c-based reimplementation of the default runtime that starts containers dramatically faster and is a low-risk drop-in replacement. Another runs each container inside a lightweight virtual machine, which is heavier but gives real hardware isolation, used in multi-tenant clusters where sharing one kernel is not trusted enough. A third implements much of the linux system-call surface in userspace as a sandbox, giving strong isolation at a modest performance cost, used by some large platforms. To use any of them, you register it in the daemon configuration and then select it per container with a runtime flag, so you can run most workloads on the default and reserve the stronger isolation for the ones that need it.

One more useful fact. The runtime supervisor can run without docker at all, and kubernetes uses it directly through a standard runtime interface. That is why a single machine's docker daemon and a kubernetes node can share one runtime instance, and why docker and the kubernetes client can sometimes see overlapping containers on the same host. It is a reminder that docker is one front end over a runtime stack that is shared across the wider container ecosystem.
